[{"id":"VR796968","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR796967.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The particle of charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive lowercase q\"><math alttext=\"positive lowercase q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> is initially located a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 R sub S\"><math alttext=\"2 R sub S\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mtext>S</mtext></msub></math></span></span> from the center of the sphere and then moved to the sphere’s center. Which of the following correctly describes the change in the electric potential energy of the particle-sphere system, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U sub P S, end sub\"><math alttext=\"delta U sub P S, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>PS</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>, when the particle is moved, and provides a valid justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR796968_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<html><body><div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\">A sphere of uniform charge density has a positive net charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"positive uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> and radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R sub s\"><math alttext=\"R sub s\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mtext>S</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. A small particle of positive charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive lowercase q\"><math alttext=\"positive lowercase q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> can be moved through space both inside the sphere of uniform charge and outside the sphere.</p></div></div></div></body></html>"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U sub P S, is greater than 0\"><math alttext=\"delta U sub P S, is greater than 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>PS</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mstyle></math></span></span>. The electric field due to the sphere’s charge does positive work on the positively charged particle.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U sub P S, is greater than 0\"><math alttext=\"delta U sub P S, is greater than 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>PS</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mstyle></math></span></span>. The motion of the positively charged particle is opposite to the direction of the electric field due to the sphere’s charge.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U sub P S, equals 0\"><math alttext=\"delta U sub P S, equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>PS</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mstyle></math></span></span>. The electric field due to the sphere’s charge is zero at the center of the sphere.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U sub P S, equals 0\"><math alttext=\"delta U sub P S, equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>PS</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mstyle></math></span></span>. As the positively charged particle is moved, positive work done outside the sphere is canceled by negative work of equal magnitude that is done inside the sphere.</p>"],"answer":1}]